ce:section.ce:para:
Peroxynitrite (ONOO−), as a member of the active nitrogen species, is produced by the diffusion controlling reaction of nitric oxide (NO) and superoxide radical anion (O2

                        •-
                     ) without enzyme catalysis [1,2]. Previous literature has reported that the ONOO− is mainly produced in mitochondria [3,4]. In organisms, the ONOO− plays a key role in signal transduction and antimicrobial activity [5], but excessive ONOO− can destroy components of cells, including proteins, DNA, lipids, and mercaptan. The accumulation of cell damage eventually leads to apoptosis and necrosis [6,7]. More and more studies have shown that the ONOO− is closely associated with many pathological conditions, such as cardiovascular disease, inflammatory disease, diabetes, Alzheimer's disease, atherosclerotic disease, neurodegenerative disease and even cancer [8–12]. Therefore, effective ONOO− detection methods are needed to facilitate early diagnosis and therapeutic monitoring of the disease.
